WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:27.170 --> 00:00:33.620
People who make it out of groups like exploitative
religious and pseudoscientific organisations

00:00:33.620 --> 00:00:36.540
are often faced with distortions from two directions.

00:00:36.540 --> 00:00:40.520
When they attempt to convey their experiences
of manipulation to members of their former group

00:00:40.520 --> 00:00:45.240
their words are magically transformed
into 'I'm mad, evil and weak'.

00:00:45.240 --> 00:00:48.780
But when they share their story 
with non-members as a cautionary tale

00:00:48.780 --> 00:00:54.460
their words are often magically transformed into
'I'm gullible, asinine and spineless'.

00:00:54.460 --> 00:00:58.300
After a while, the apostates realise
they're in the noonesland of the unheard.

00:00:58.300 --> 00:01:01.740
And it begins to become clear
why these groups continue to thrive —

00:01:01.740 --> 00:01:03.960
groups with a talent for bending truth,

00:01:03.960 --> 00:01:07.820
preaching love while denouncing
non-members as a subhuman underclass;

00:01:07.820 --> 00:01:11.520
claiming to champion peace,
while committing acts of barbarism;

00:01:11.520 --> 00:01:15.420
pontificating about family values while
tearing up countless homes;

00:01:15.420 --> 00:01:21.560
promising freedom and enlightenment while
enforcing ignorance and exercising total control

00:01:21.560 --> 00:01:24.600
I want to explore some of
the mechanics of manipulative groups,

00:01:24.600 --> 00:01:28.160
dispatching some of the stereotypes
about the people who get recruited by them,

00:01:28.160 --> 00:01:32.000
and reflecting on preventive measures
we might take to avoid recruitment.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:35.460
But if there's just one thing
I really want to do in this video,

00:01:35.460 --> 00:01:39.540
it's to communicate the importance of
acknowledging a simple but profound fact:

00:01:39.549 --> 00:01:43.749
we can be manipulated

00:01:48.040 --> 00:01:50.620
At a press conference on manipulative groups

00:01:50.620 --> 00:01:52.780
Ian reveals he lost tens of thousands of dollars

00:01:52.780 --> 00:01:55.180
When he was recruited by a group who proposed that

00:01:55.180 --> 00:01:59.800
clusters of alien spirits are attached
to all humans, keeping us from a full potential.

00:01:59.800 --> 00:02:04.980
Ian tells us how he and the other group members
paid through the nose — and every other orifice —

00:02:04.980 --> 00:02:09.340
for a special kind of counselling which they
were told would rid them of these spirits.

00:02:09.340 --> 00:02:14.260
They were told that once these spirits were gone,
they would be the primary causal agents of their lives

00:02:14.260 --> 00:02:18.960
with skills such as telekinesis, total recall
and mastery over illness.

00:02:18.960 --> 00:02:21.060
No evidence was given for any of this.

00:02:21.060 --> 00:02:24.880
The alien story was the unsubstantiated
revelation claim of the group's founder

00:02:24.880 --> 00:02:27.660
and no records have ever been
produced of a single person

00:02:27.660 --> 00:02:30.840
gaining any of the special powers
or knowledge described.

00:02:30.840 --> 00:02:32.920
What do we think of Ian?

00:02:32.920 --> 00:02:34.920
Does he lack intelligence?

00:02:34.920 --> 00:02:37.500
No. His intelligence is above average.

00:02:37.500 --> 00:02:42.780
He's a highly creative, resourceful man —&nbsp;that's why
the group considered him such a juicy prospect.

00:02:42.780 --> 00:02:46.380
Is he a bit credulous —
quick to accept whatever he's told?

00:02:46.380 --> 00:02:50.560
No. In fact, by default, he's a cautious skeptical fellow.

00:02:50.560 --> 00:02:54.560
Is he driven by narcissism,
desiring supremacy over others?

00:02:54.560 --> 00:02:58.480
No. He's always been compelled
by deeply humanitarian instincts.

00:02:58.480 --> 00:03:00.720
Of course there are folks out there who are ....

00:03:00.720 --> 00:03:06.260
gullible, obtuse, submissive,
power-hungry, escapist, lazy.

00:03:06.260 --> 00:03:08.260
But it's a huge mistake to assume that

00:03:08.260 --> 00:03:13.380
successful recruitment into manipulative groups
depends on the presence of these kinds of traits.

00:03:13.380 --> 00:03:17.740
And while we're hunting for them in Ian's case,
we're missing six crucial words:

00:03:17.740 --> 00:03:19.680
'he was recruited by a group'.

00:03:19.680 --> 00:03:21.840
He was subjected to a process.

00:03:21.840 --> 00:03:26.780
The idea of alien spirit clusters wasn't presented
to him in the bald way he presented it to us.

00:03:26.780 --> 00:03:30.060
Ian was carefully steered
through a sequence of experiences

00:03:30.060 --> 00:03:32.920
so that by the time the alien
spirits concept was mentioned

00:03:32.920 --> 00:03:35.900
a range of key psychological elements had
been established

00:03:35.900 --> 00:03:39.380
to ease its entry and help insulate it from criticism.

00:03:39.380 --> 00:03:42.080
Later on, I'll be looking at how this was done.

00:03:42.080 --> 00:03:46.100
Just as we can become distracted
by the red herring of personality deficiencies

00:03:46.100 --> 00:03:49.720
we can become misled by the notion
of predisposing circumstance.

00:03:49.720 --> 00:03:52.920
Some psychologists have generated
lists of situational factors

00:03:52.920 --> 00:03:55.500
that can leave us vulnerable to manipulative groups.

00:03:55.500 --> 00:04:00.040
Factors like 'weak family bonds'
or 'recent bereavement'.

00:04:00.040 --> 00:04:03.600
Problem is, when we don't find
ourselves reflected in those items,

00:04:03.600 --> 00:04:06.320
we can be left with the impression we're not vulnerable.

00:04:06.320 --> 00:04:08.860
When we see an item like 'weak family bonds'

00:04:08.860 --> 00:04:11.380
we might satisfy ourselves that we not risk

00:04:11.380 --> 00:04:13.520
because we have strong family bonds.

00:04:13.520 --> 00:04:16.380
But strong family bonds can put people at risk too.

00:04:16.380 --> 00:04:18.620
Many people are recruited by relative.

00:04:18.620 --> 00:04:20.740
And if your whole family's been indoctrinated,

00:04:20.740 --> 00:04:22.980
you could be born into a manipulative group.

00:04:22.980 --> 00:04:26.120
In these cases, even if you wake up
and smell the Kool Aid

00:04:26.120 --> 00:04:29.220
strong family bonds might keep you
feeling trapped inside the group

00:04:29.220 --> 00:04:32.180
under the threat of disconnection from your family.

00:04:32.180 --> 00:04:35.620
Members of manipulative groups are a
diverse population

00:04:35.620 --> 00:04:38.400
and it serves us well to think creatively

00:04:38.400 --> 00:04:41.160
about how these groups might hook us in.

00:04:46.639 --> 00:04:50.919
Some of us go through life convinced we
possess an almost clinical objectivity —

00:04:50.920 --> 00:04:55.300
that, barring deliberate deceptions or the
odd quirky optical illusion,

00:04:55.300 --> 00:05:01.600
we generally perceived reality as it actually is;
and that we make decisions on a firmly rational basis.

00:05:01.600 --> 00:05:06.280
For over a century, social psychologists
 have been ripping that fantasy apart,

00:05:06.280 --> 00:05:10.760
conducting experiments that elicit the most bizarre,
counterintuitive human responses

00:05:10.760 --> 00:05:13.560
and exposing a gamut of distinct biases

00:05:13.560 --> 00:05:17.400
each of which distorts our perception
in its own specific way.

00:05:17.400 --> 00:05:21.280
A landmark concept in social psychology 
emerged in the 1950s

00:05:21.280 --> 00:05:26.020
that provided a framework on which to untangle
all kinds of paradoxical human behaviour.

00:05:26.020 --> 00:05:28.980
Leon Festinger's theory of cognitive dissonance.

00:05:28.980 --> 00:05:33.860
It also described arguably the biggest implement
in the toolboxes of manipulative groups

00:05:33.860 --> 00:05:37.240
who not only rely on it to keep
existing members under their influence

00:05:37.240 --> 00:05:40.760
but also actively exploit it to recruit new members.

00:05:40.760 --> 00:05:45.000
Festinger and his colleagues proposed that
 we seek consistency within our cognitions —

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:48.480
our thoughts, emotions, memories, perceptions —

00:05:48.490 --> 00:05:53.080
and that when we discover an inconsistency
we experience a psychological discomfort

00:05:53.080 --> 00:05:55.900
that motivates us to try and reduce that conflict.

00:05:55.900 --> 00:05:58.460
So, what does dissonance look like in action?

00:05:58.460 --> 00:06:02.200
Say we've been told to believe
all members of group A evil.

00:06:02.200 --> 00:06:06.880
One day, a friend we've always known to be
a good person reveals she's a member of group A.

00:06:06.880 --> 00:06:10.620
This arouses dissonance because
our experience contradicts our belief.

00:06:10.620 --> 00:06:12.980
We can reduce this dissonance in a number of ways.

00:06:12.980 --> 00:06:16.680
If we're not hugely invested in the belief,
we might opt for method one:

00:06:16.680 --> 00:06:18.240
simply adjust our belief.

00:06:18.240 --> 00:06:22.540
We might, for instance, change it to:
'not all members of group A are evil'.

00:06:22.540 --> 00:06:25.320
If we're equally invested
in the belief and the friendship

00:06:25.320 --> 00:06:29.020
we might try to preserve both using method two: denial.

00:06:29.020 --> 00:06:32.260
We might refuse to believe
our friend is a true member of group A,

00:06:32.260 --> 00:06:36.200
granting her special exemption
because she's just not like those other folks.

00:06:36.200 --> 00:06:40.200
If we're more invested in the belief than
the friendship, we might go for method three:

00:06:40.200 --> 00:06:42.200
select confirming information.

00:06:42.340 --> 00:06:47.120
Here, we cherry-pick information consistent with
our belief and ignore information that contradicts it.

00:06:47.120 --> 00:06:51.300
Any flaws in our friend's behaviour
or attitudes can be turned against her

00:06:51.300 --> 00:06:53.160
while her goodness is ignored.

00:06:53.160 --> 00:06:56.460
Festinger and his colleagues noted
that when we experience dissonance

00:06:56.460 --> 00:07:00.820
we'll tend to avoid information or situations
that threaten further dissonance.

00:07:00.820 --> 00:07:04.420
For instance, if we've denied that
our friend is a member of group A,

00:07:04.420 --> 00:07:07.440
we'll want to avoid the subject in future conversations.

00:07:07.440 --> 00:07:11.380
Or, if we've used selective information
to cast our friend as evil,

00:07:11.380 --> 00:07:16.160
we might quickly break off contact to avoid
giving her the chance to reason with us.

00:07:16.160 --> 00:07:20.100
But sometimes our response to dissonance
is so horrendously distorted

00:07:20.100 --> 00:07:23.080
that it makes us almost
invulnerable to further dissonance,

00:07:23.080 --> 00:07:25.260
reducing our need for avoidance.

00:07:25.260 --> 00:07:29.980
For example, say we look for evidence
that our friend's evil, but can't find any?

00:07:29.980 --> 00:07:33.420
What if — time after time — we're confronted with good?

00:07:33.420 --> 00:07:37.400
How can we possibly preserve a belief
that all members of group A are evil now?

00:07:37.400 --> 00:07:39.820
Well, all is not as bleak as it seems.

00:07:39.820 --> 00:07:42.560
We have method four: repackaging.

00:07:42.560 --> 00:07:45.400
Believing that no member of
group A could possibly be good

00:07:45.400 --> 00:07:49.340
We could repackage our experience 
of our friend's goodness as something it's not.

00:07:49.340 --> 00:07:54.360
We might tell ourselves she was only pretending
to be good — it was all an act, a deception.

00:07:54.360 --> 00:07:56.780
And isn't that the most insidious evil of all?

00:07:56.780 --> 00:07:59.260
The evil that disguises itself as good?

00:07:59.260 --> 00:08:01.100
The wolf in sheep's clothing?

00:08:01.100 --> 00:08:03.820
We've now put our friend in a no-win position.

00:08:03.820 --> 00:08:06.900
Even her goodness has now
become evidence of her evil.

00:08:06.900 --> 00:08:08.780
Now we don't even have to avoid her.

00:08:08.780 --> 00:08:12.740
Anything she does — good or bad — confirms our belief.

00:08:12.740 --> 00:08:18.060
Later on, I'll be looking at how manipulative groups
explicitly employ these kinds of extreme contortions

00:08:18.060 --> 00:08:20.360
to put their critics in a no-win position

00:08:20.360 --> 00:08:23.640
and keep their members under psychological lockdown.

00:08:23.640 --> 00:08:28.760
Various experiments have shown how dissonance
can be actively exploited to induce positive responses.

00:08:28.760 --> 00:08:30.480
In a 1959 paper

00:08:30.480 --> 00:08:35.520
Aronson and Mills investigated the role of initiation
procedures in attitudes toward groups.

00:08:35.520 --> 00:08:40.220
They advertised for female subjects to join
a group discussing the psychology of sex.

00:08:40.220 --> 00:08:44.580
But before being accepted, subjects were told
they had to pass an embarrassment test.

00:08:44.580 --> 00:08:46.580
There were three experimental conditions.

00:08:46.580 --> 00:08:48.940
Subjects in the 'severe initiation' condition

00:08:48.940 --> 00:08:52.480
read out loud to the experimenter
a list of words considered obscene

00:08:52.480 --> 00:08:54.880
as well as sexually explicit passages.

00:08:54.880 --> 00:09:00.020
Subjects in the 'mild initiation' condition read out loud a list of sexual but non-obscene terms.

00:09:00.020 --> 00:09:03.600
Subjects in the 'no initiation' condition weren't screened.

00:09:03.600 --> 00:09:08.920
Each subject then listened to the same pre-recorded
discussion,&nbsp;deliberately designed to be boring.

00:09:08.920 --> 00:09:11.300
They then rated their perceptions of the group.

00:09:11.300 --> 00:09:14.820
Intuitively, one might think the more severe the initiation

00:09:14.820 --> 00:09:18.040
the more the discussion's
dreariness would be accentuated.

00:09:18.040 --> 00:09:19.560
But the reverse was true.

00:09:19.560 --> 00:09:23.160
Subjects from the 'severe' condition showed
the strongest liking for the group,

00:09:23.160 --> 00:09:27.560
rating it as significantly more attractive
compared with the ratings of the other groups.

00:09:27.560 --> 00:09:33.380
Aronson and Mills explained this counter-intuitive finding in terms of dissonance between two cognitions:

00:09:33.380 --> 00:09:37.900
subjects in the 'severe' condition had gone through a difficult experience to join the group,

00:09:37.900 --> 00:09:39.920
but the group wasn't worthwhile.

00:09:39.920 --> 00:09:44.320
When we invest time, effort, money,
emotion, in an enterprise

00:09:44.320 --> 00:09:46.920
we want to believe our investment isn't wasted.

00:09:46.920 --> 00:09:51.040
So we repackage useless enterprises as useful.

00:09:51.040 --> 00:09:53.320
This result, supported by other studies,

00:09:53.320 --> 00:09:57.160
demonstrates how worthless groups
can be made to appear worthwhile.

00:09:57.160 --> 00:10:02.660
A decade later, Knox and Inkster showed
just how quickly actions can induce attitudes.

00:10:02.660 --> 00:10:07.760
At a racetrack, 69 bettors were asked
by one experimenter, just prior to betting

00:10:07.760 --> 00:10:09.900
to rate the chances of their horse winning.

00:10:09.900 --> 00:10:14.500
72 bettors were asked by a second
experimenter, just after placing their bets.

00:10:14.500 --> 00:10:19.520
Using a 7-point scale, on average,
pre-bettors rated their chances 'fair'.

00:10:19.520 --> 00:10:22.220
Post-bettors rated their chances 'good'.

00:10:22.220 --> 00:10:26.440
One bettor, who'd given a rating
to the pre-bet experimenter and placed his bet

00:10:26.440 --> 00:10:30.900
then spotted the post-bet experimenter
and asked if the two were working together.

00:10:30.900 --> 00:10:34.920
He then enquired if he could now
change his rating from 'fair' to 'excellent'.

00:10:34.930 --> 00:10:38.410
Studies like this show the important
role behaviour plays in dissonance.

00:10:38.410 --> 00:10:41.390
In fact, when we're looking at the
components of dissonance

00:10:41.390 --> 00:10:47.290
we could divide them into three broad classes:
behaviour, emotions and thoughts.

00:10:47.290 --> 00:10:51.930
Pull hard enough on one and, in our drive
for consistency, the others will follow

00:10:51.930 --> 00:10:56.600
When we behave as if we're committed,
our thoughts and emotions often fall in line.

00:10:56.600 --> 00:10:59.700
But how do we become
so heavily invested in an idea

00:10:59.700 --> 00:11:02.780
that we find ourselves twisting
concepts into their opposites —

00:11:02.780 --> 00:11:07.540
bending 'good' into 'evil', 'love' into 'hate' —
just to preserve that idea?

00:11:07.540 --> 00:11:11.660
While cognitive dissonance studies tend
to focus on the conflict between two ideas

00:11:11.660 --> 00:11:14.580
those two ideas don't of course exist in isolation.

00:11:14.580 --> 00:11:17.600
Networks of reinforcing ideas often lie behind them.

00:11:17.600 --> 00:11:21.380
For instance, regarding our
hypothetical belief that group A is evil

00:11:21.380 --> 00:11:25.680
maybe our entire community has
always vehemently condemned group A.

00:11:25.680 --> 00:11:29.560
We might have behaved hatefully toward some
members of group A ourselves in the past

00:11:29.560 --> 00:11:32.080
based solely on this prejudice.

00:11:32.080 --> 00:11:36.500
We might also have seen group A sympathisers
being attacked and ostracised.

00:11:36.500 --> 00:11:40.960
If it turns out group A isn't evil,
we have some tough realities to face.

00:11:40.960 --> 00:11:44.340
First, we have to admit
our entire community is wrong.

00:11:44.350 --> 00:11:49.220
This could tap into some hefty issues
around trust, loyalty and credibility.

00:11:49.220 --> 00:11:52.940
Second, we'll have to admit our own
hateful behaviour was unjustified.

00:11:52.940 --> 00:11:56.380
This could have big implications for our self-image.

00:11:56.380 --> 00:12:00.380
Third, we now face being attacked
and ostracised if we defend groups A

00:12:00.380 --> 00:12:03.680
which taps into our ideas of safety and security.

00:12:03.680 --> 00:12:07.240
These tough realities might
feel intensely threatening to us.

00:12:07.240 --> 00:12:12.140
But the threat goes away if we can find some way
of preserving our belief that group A is evil.

00:12:12.140 --> 00:12:17.080
So it is that we might find ourselves turning on
our friend just to preserve a false belief.

00:12:17.080 --> 00:12:21.760
And of course this might in itself make it even harder
to admit our mistake in the future

00:12:21.760 --> 00:12:23.920
because adding to all the other tough realities

00:12:23.920 --> 00:12:27.360
we'll now have to admit we betrayed a good friend.

00:12:27.360 --> 00:12:31.040
Our minds are not objective, logical machines.

00:12:31.040 --> 00:12:35.660
Our minds are vast networks of ideas,
striving not necessarily for truth

00:12:35.660 --> 00:12:37.660
but for internal consistency.

00:12:37.670 --> 00:12:41.400
In view of this, it's plain to see why childhood
is by far the most preferred period

00:12:41.400 --> 00:12:44.100
for indoctrination into manipulative groups.

00:12:44.100 --> 00:12:46.880
Parents and guardians can
get in there right at the start

00:12:46.880 --> 00:12:49.380
and insert any unsubstantiated concept they like

00:12:49.380 --> 00:12:53.360
into the child's basic
initial framework without resistance.

00:12:53.360 --> 00:12:55.240
Being implanted so early

00:12:55.240 --> 00:12:57.560
they stand a good chance of becoming core beliefs

00:12:57.560 --> 00:13:03.500
with rich networks of ideas reinforcing them including
strong associations of identity of many levels —

00:13:03.500 --> 00:13:07.860
individual, family, culture, perhaps nationality.

00:13:07.860 --> 00:13:13.420
If the unsubstantiated concept is later challenged,
threatening tremors could be felt in all of these areas.

00:13:13.420 --> 00:13:19.280
Indoctrinating adults who've already developed
an advanced cognitive network isn't so straightforward.

00:13:19.280 --> 00:13:22.700
Manipulative groups often have to
insert their unsubstantiated ideas

00:13:22.700 --> 00:13:25.460
into a distinctly inhospitable environment.

00:13:25.460 --> 00:13:28.640
And it's no coincidence that in order to achieve that goal

00:13:28.640 --> 00:13:33.540
some groups will try to mimic those
childhood conditions by infantilising adults.

00:13:33.540 --> 00:13:38.040
When I was a christian we were repeatedly told
that we needed to be like children —

00:13:38.040 --> 00:13:40.180
trusting and dependent on Yahweh

00:13:40.180 --> 00:13:43.300
which in the total absence of any evidence of Yahweh

00:13:43.300 --> 00:13:47.940
translates to: 'trusting and dependent on
the humans who claim to represent Yahweh'.

00:13:47.940 --> 00:13:50.380
And there was a nice little threat
thrown in there.

00:13:50.380 --> 00:13:53.400
If you didn't become like children,
you'd never get into heaven.

00:13:53.400 --> 00:13:57.240
In a similar vein we were told:
'Lean not on your own understanding'.

00:13:57.240 --> 00:13:59.280
'Do not be wise in your own eyes'.

00:13:59.280 --> 00:14:02.080
The message in all these
commands couldn't be clearer.

00:14:02.080 --> 00:14:06.960
Wherever your ideas conflict with those of the group,
it's your ideas that need to change.

00:14:06.960 --> 00:14:12.100
Folks who submit to these commands can now have vast amounts of their cognitive network rewritten

00:14:12.100 --> 00:14:15.160
without substantial resistance — just like childhood.

00:14:15.160 --> 00:14:19.640
Of course, adult recruits are more of a bonus
than a necessity for the major world religions

00:14:19.640 --> 00:14:22.660
who are guaranteed a steady influx of child recruits

00:14:22.660 --> 00:14:26.600
As long as the abuse of childhood
religious indoctrination continues.

00:14:26.600 --> 00:14:29.140
Other groups who are more reliant on adult recruits

00:14:29.150 --> 00:14:33.170
often have to manipulate cognitive
dissonance in more subtle ways.

00:14:39.190 --> 00:14:42.230
Let's go back to Ian and see how he gets recruited

00:14:42.230 --> 00:14:45.730
by a group claiming clusters of
alien spirits are attached to us all

00:14:45.730 --> 00:14:47.420
keeping us from a full potential.

00:14:47.420 --> 00:14:51.160
Ian is approached on the street
by a woman with a personality questionnaire.

00:14:51.160 --> 00:14:54.320
He agrees to accompany her inside
the official premises behind her

00:14:54.320 --> 00:14:56.460
where he spends half an hour completing it.

00:14:56.470 --> 00:15:01.830
His results show him to be
unstable, depressed, nervous and overly critical.

00:15:01.830 --> 00:15:03.600
These conflict with his self-image.

00:15:03.600 --> 00:15:09.200
But the woman talks with him for a further half hour about his life — his frustrations, his disappointments —

00:15:09.200 --> 00:15:12.180
and draws tentative connections with his results.

00:15:12.180 --> 00:15:16.220
She says her group runs courses that can
help him become a more effective person.

00:15:16.220 --> 00:15:19.180
Ian's natural caution stops him
